  "prompt": "Thermodynamics: What is the difference between wet steam and dry steam?",
  "response": "In thermodynamics, the difference between wet steam and dry steam is related to their moisture content:\n\nWet Steam:\n- Contains both water vapor and liquid water droplets\n- Temperature is at or below saturation temperature\n- Moisture content greater than 0%\n- Less efficient for power generation\n- Lower energy transfer capabilities\n- Can cause erosion in turbine blades\n\nDry Steam:\n- Contains only water vapor/steam\n- Temperature is above saturation temperature\n- No liquid water droplets present\n- 100% vapor state\n- More efficient for power generation\n- Better energy transfer properties\n- Less damaging to equipment\n- Typically found in geothermal or high-temperature steam sources\n\nKey distinguishing factor is the presence of liquid water droplets, which affects steam's thermodynamic properties and performance in various applications like power generation and industrial processes.",
